name: Jeder einmal in Berlin!
comments: In 1927 the Berlin authorities created a board which was to be responsible for the city's advertising campaigns. Its first slogan was presented graphically: "Jeder einmal in Berlin", where the six letters of "Berlin" build the pillar of a stylized Brandenburg Gate. The meaning of the slogan is "Everyone should be at least once in Berlin". In proper German the complete phrase would be "Jeder sollte einmal in Berlin sein".

name: Beautiful City [1990s lyrics]
comments: In the years since the original song was written, Schwartz described the lyric as 'too sentimental'. In the early 1990s, when planning for a Los Angeles production of Godspell, Schwartz changed the lyrics influenced by the aftermath of the riots in Los Angeles. Though the Los Angeles production never came into being, the newer version is the one predominantly used in Godspell productions since then. Original first verse: Come sing me sweet rejoicing / Come sing me love / We're not afraid of voicing / All the things / We're dreaming of / Oh, high and low / And everywhere we go 1990s first verse: Out of the ruins and rubble / Out of the smoke / Out of our night of struggle / Can we see a ray of hope / One pale thin ray reaching for the day?

name: The Highwayman
comments: A romantic ballad poem irst published in the August 1906 issue of Blackwood's Magazine, based in Edinburgh, Scotland. The following year it was included in Noyes' collection, Forty Singing Seamen and Other Poems. In 1995 it was voted 15th in the BBC's poll for "The Nation's Favourite Poems". The poem, set in 18th-century rural England, tells the story of an unnamed highwayman who is in love with Bess, an innkeeper's daughter. Betrayed to the authorities by Tim, a jealous ostler, the highwayman escapes ambush when Bess sacrifices her life to warn him. Learning of her death, he is killed in a futile attempt at revenge. In the final stanza, the ghosts of the lovers meet again on winter nights.
